c. The Codex universitatis pragensis X. D. 11. (Β).

In spite of the care with which Nicolaus Faulfisch and his com- panion addressed themselves to their task, A contains a number of errors, and many passages as they stand in A will yield no sense. Al being then only a copy of A, the prospect of the restoration of a correct text of “De ecclesia” would have been very poor, had Ι not lately been so fortunate as to find a Codex1 in which the treatise is in a far better condition in these very passages. This manuscript, which came into my hands almost by chance in the year 1883, is the Codex X. D. 11. of the University library of Prague.

This Codex, to which we will refer as B, a large folio volume (31cm >< 22cm) consists of 214 paper leaves, of which the last is left blank. lt contains first the tract “De ecclesia⁷' (fol. 13—1303) and Wyclif’s “De officio regis'' (1302—2iob). There is besides in the appendix an extract from the treatise “De officio regis’' (fol. 210b — 212³) and extracts from the first twelve chapters of “De ecclesia'’ (fol. 2122—214b). The external arrangement of A is very much the same as that of Β. Here too every leaf has four columns of forty—three lines.

The Codex was at one time in the possession of Magister Peter of Zepekow2‚ a friend and follower of Hus. Peter of Zepekow was a man of considerable mark at the University of Prague, where he was professor up to the time of his death, which took place in 1431.
